negative coefficients at the upper end of the happiness scale. Those who
describe religion as “Somewhat important” show a coefficient of –0.189 at
happiness level 9 and –0.668 at level 10, indicating markedly lower odds of
reaching the top categories. The “Not very important” group displays even larger
reductions, with coefficients of –0.341 and –0.936. The most secular group,
reporting religion as “Not at all important,” shows substantial declines of
–0.495 at happiness level 9 and –0.815 at level 10. These results are uniformly
statistically significant at the 1 percent level and suggest that higher
religiosity is associated with higher reported well-being even after controlling
for income, age, marital status, education, and demographic factors.
The steady decline across categories indicates a monotonic relationship:
as religiosity weakens, so do the odds of reporting higher life satisfaction.
Gender differences appear small but statistically meaningful in some thresholds.
With men as the omitted category, the coefficient for women is negative at
several points in the distribution, including –0.086** at happiness level 8 and
–0.109 at level 10. These estimates indicate that women have slightly lower odds
of being in the upper happiness categories compared to men. The effects are
modest in magnitude but statistically significant, suggesting that even after
controlling for income, age, education, marital status, and other factors,
a small happiness gap exists between men and women, with women reporting lower
probabilities of the highest satisfaction levels. At intermediate thresholds,
the coefficients are close to zero and not statistically significant, indicating
that the gender gap primarily emerges in the transition toward the highest
well-being categories.
Overall, the results show that income is a strong and consistent predictor of
higher life satisfaction, though gains taper at the top end. Happiness follows
a clear U-shape over the life cycle: midlife respondents are significantly less
happy, while those aged 65 and over show the highest odds of reporting strong
well-being. Marital status exerts one of the largest effects, with married
individuals substantially happier than widowed, separated, divorced, or
never-married respondents. Higher education also corresponds to higher happiness,
particularly at intermediate and upper-middle satisfaction levels. Religiosity
displays a strong gradient, with those who consider religion less important
reporting markedly lower happiness. Gender differences are smaller but indicate
slightly lower odds for women at the very highest happiness levels.
Taken together, the evidence shows that while income clearly improves happiness,
social and demographic factors—especially age, partnership, education, and
religiosity—play equally central roles in shaping subjective well-being.
")
